# Function to plot team data
def plot_teams(data, ax):
    plotted_teams = set() 
    
    # for loop to run through each team in the dataset plot them and get their primary and outline colors
    # and see if they won the super bowl in a given year
    for team in data.columns:
        if team not in plotted_teams:
            primary_color = team_colors.get(team, 'black')
            outline_color = team_outline_colors.get(team, 'white') 
            ax.plot(data.index, data[team], marker='o', color=primary_color, label=team, markeredgecolor=outline_color) 
            plotted_teams.add(team) 
            if team in super_bowl_winners.values():
                winner_years = [year for year, winner in super_bowl_winners.items() if winner == team]
                for year in winner_years:
                    wins = data.loc[year, team]
                    ax.scatter(year, wins, marker='o', color='none', edgecolors='gold', s=100, linewidths=2)
                    
    # added the legend outside of the graph                
    ax.legend(loc='upper left', bbox_to_anchor=(1.02, 1), borderaxespad=0, ncol=2)
    
     # I decided to make the background white and grid lines white as to mimic an actual football field
    ax.grid(True, color='white')
    ax.set_facecolor((0, 0.5019607843137255, 0, 0.75))
    
    # I then set the axis labels and tick positions
    ax.set_xticks(range(2003, 2024)) 
    ax.set_xticklabels([str(year) if year % 3 == 0 else '' for year in range(2003, 2024)])
    ax.set_xlabel('NFL Season')
    ax.set_ylabel('# of Wins')

    
# code to actually plot the graph
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 8))
plot_teams(yearly_wins, ax)
ax.set_title('NFL Wins By Season - All Teams') 
plt.tight_layout()
#savefig method is to save and export the final result to get as a .png file
plt.savefig('INFSCI_1520_Final_ForReal.png')  
plt.show()

ipywidgets version

I felt as though the initial graph is somewhat cluttered. Having only 16 values with 32 teams leads to a lot of overlap and visibility issues so I made an interactive version using the ipywidgets module that filters the graph based on each conference and division

In[3]:
import ipywidgets as widgets
from IPython.display import display, clear_output
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Get divisions for conference and adds an all option
def get_divisions(conference):
    divisions = sorted({info["division"] for info in team_info.values() if info["conference"] == conference})
    return ["All"] + divisions

# Function to update the plot based on selected filters
def update_plot(conference, division):
    plot_output.clear_output(wait=True)
    with plot_output:
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 8))
        # If "all" is selected, include all divisions in the conference
        filtered_teams = [
            team for team, info in team_info.items()
            if info["conference"] == conference and (division == "All" or info["division"] == division)
        ]
        for team in filtered_teams:
            if team in yearly_wins.columns:
                ax.plot(
                    yearly_wins.index, yearly_wins[team],
                    label=team,
                    color=team_colors.get(team, 'black'),
                    marker='o',
                    markeredgecolor=team_outline_colors.get(team, 'white')
                )
                if team in super_bowl_winners.values():
                    winner_years = [year for year, winner in super_bowl_winners.items() if winner == team]
                    for year in winner_years:
                        if year in yearly_wins.index:
                            ax.scatter(year, yearly_wins.loc[year, team], marker='o', color='none',
                                       edgecolors='gold', s=100, linewidths=2)

        title_div = division if division != "All" else "All Divisions"
        ax.set_title(f"NFL Wins: {conference} - {title_div}")
        ax.set_xlabel("NFL Season")
        ax.set_ylabel("# of Wins")
        ax.grid(True, color='white')
        ax.set_facecolor((0, 0.5019607843137255, 0, 0.75))
        ax.set_xticks(range(2003, 2024))
        ax.set_xticklabels([str(year) if year % 3 == 0 else '' for year in range(2003, 2024)])
        ax.legend(loc='upper left', bbox_to_anchor=(1.02, 1), borderaxespad=0, ncol=2)
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

# Dropdown widgets
conference_dropdown = widgets.Dropdown(
    options=sorted(set(info['conference'] for info in team_info.values())),
    value='AFC',
    description='Conference:'
)

division_dropdown = widgets.Dropdown(
    options=get_divisions('AFC'),
    value='All',
    description='Division:'
)

# output area for the plot
plot_output = widgets.Output()

# When conference changes, update divisions
def on_conference_change(change):
    new_conf = change['new']
    new_divs = get_divisions(new_conf)
    division_dropdown.options = new_divs
    division_dropdown.value = new_divs[0]  # Set to "All"

# and then once the division changes, the plot is updates and the new graph shows
def on_division_change(change):
    update_plot(conference_dropdown.value, division_dropdown.value)

# creates and display the interactive dashboard UI and connects user input to update functions
conference_dropdown.observe(on_conference_change, names='value')
division_dropdown.observe(on_division_change, names='value')
controls = widgets.HBox([conference_dropdown, division_dropdown])
dashboard = widgets.VBox([controls, plot_output])
display(dashboard)

# updates the plot
update_plot(conference_dropdown.value, division_dropdown.value)
